      ],
      "flags": {},
      "order": 1,
      "mode": 0,
      "inputs": [],
      "outputs": [],
      "title": "README",
      "properties": {},
      "widgets_values": [
        "\nThis workflow serves as a reference for performing inpainting using Z-Image Turbo and the power nodes.\n\nInpainting Process:\n  1. Load the image into the \"Load Image\" node.\n  2. Right-click inside the node -> \"Open in MaskEditor\"\n  3. Edit the mask - it can have sharp edges since the encoder will apply blur.\n  4. Within the mask editor, press \"Save\" to set the mask.\n  5. Enter a prompt describing how you want the final image to look.\n  6. Run the workflow and the masked area will be modified.\n\nKey Points:\n\n  * In my tests, not using styles works better (style = none)\n\n  * The inpainting process may perform better with \"denoise = 0.85\" in Z-Sampler,\n    though this was a basic adjustment by me, other denoise values might work even better,\n    it's worth trying.\n\n  * VAE Encode settings:\n\n     - \"output_size = medium\" resizes the image to an optimal size for z-image processing.\n       Inpainting should work at any resolution, so there's also an option \"same_as_input\"\n       which maintains the original image size.\n\n     - \"mask_blur_pixels\" specifies the width in pixels of the blur effect applied to the mask.\n       It helps blend the original image smoothly with the model-generated part. Since this\n       value is in pixels, it depends greatly on your specific image. (smaller images may\n       require lower values while very large images might need higher ones)."
      ],
      "color": "#432",
      "bgcolor": "#653"
    },
    {
      "id": 103,
